```Bittensor is a mining network, similar to Bitcoin, that offers censorship-resistant access to a decentralized network of machine learning models. Okay, but what does that mean in practice? You register a hotkey on a computer, as Kat mentioned, typically virtual machines - some form of container. You load all required dependencies, load your model, and deploy it as a miner under a registered hotkey. This compute can be contributed through local hardware, although those requirements would be at *least* 24gb vRam. I believe there will be much opportunity for those who have Nvidia cards with that baseline of hardware to host models on the network.

That being said, this compute *can* be rented on the cloud. It doesn't *have* to be, hence why this is decentralized - anybody could plug in given they have the required amount of compute locally. This requires serious investments of time, effort, and often finances. Servers and hardware aren't cheap! Neither is TAO, which is required to register a hotkey on the network in order to mine - and losing a hotkey means you'll have to recycle_register to gain another. 

To say the least, the mechanisms running the Bittensor network rely on various actors throughout the decentralized field of computer scientists hosting models, validators, and pushing the network further by hosting AI and creating valuable services for all of the community to benefit from. Afternoon Zylon and thank you for the good question! To debrief in here for you and your friend, both `SingularityNET `and `Bittensor `are ambitious projects working on decentralized AI in the space as you might know, but the vision of the solution being built and approaches are pretty different.

As you have heard already, `SingularityNET `is primarily a marketplace for AI services. Mainly being designed to let anyone create, share, and monetize AI services at scale. Imagine like creating a space where AI models can be bought and sold, and their AGI token is used as a medium of exchange in that marketplace.

On the other hand, our Core Team is creating a decentralized machine-learning network. And Bittensor is like a giant brain giving access to multiple datasets or models at the same place for the end user, you contribute to the network by running a node and participating in the model training process, nodes in the network (miners) use their computational resources to train machine learning models. Validators assess the performance of these models and reward the nodes based on their contribution to the network's collective intelligence to give you a overview. `Bittensor `emphasizes the creation and development of more advanced, collective machine learning models through the collaboration of nodes in the network.

So the focus in between both are quite different. Bear in mind that vision of our Core Team is building decentralized network where AI models learn from each other in a peer-to-peer manner. Think of it as the future of AI, being built right here and vision is to create a pure market for artificial intelligence, an incentivized arena in which consumers and producers of this valuable commodity can interact in a trustless, open and transparent context, and I believe this will give you clear context on discussion with your Friend to keep it further!:bittensor:

Dang ya beat me to it, but great explanation Oliver - I would like to also add in that Bittensor allows anybody to plug into the network, given they have the TAO to register a key and the knowledge to serve a miner properly. In the future, Bittensor will serve multi-modality, meaning txt2img, voice, etc - all will become main-net features that people can serve their custom models on for incentive(theoretically, I don't actually know how those models will be incentivized tbh). Miners are going to not only be incentivized with TAO for LLMs, but with the advent of more client-facing applications, we will be able to interact with the network in a variety of ways - ways that further benefit all participants of the network, from clients to validators alike. 

Bittensor is the battlegrounds of Open-source LLMs, so to speak, where-in the models being served fight for incentive via the miners that fine-tune and build such models to deploy on the network. In theory, the better your model, the better your incentives - and competition does appear to be quite fierce. 

I'm not going to say SingularityNet is useless, I'm sure they have accomplished a ton, but to say the two networks are the same is to compare apples to oranges. The two aren't even attempting to accomplish the same things IMO, as Oliver mentioned above: Bittensor is an open network of collaboration(anybody can plug in), and it contains(imo) some of the brightest minds within the computer science industry. Anybody is welcome to test their skills here, and we encourage it - one may even say we incentivize it.
